@unpublished{BairdPrep,
	Abstract = {The development of the settlement at Shuna between 5200 and 2400 BC
	
	
	An understanding of the scale of the community at Shuna plays an important
	role in how we conceive the nature of interactions within that community
	and between Shuna and surrounding communities. Aspects of density
	and layout of household and public spaces also affect our understandings
	of household interactions, how households and individuals negotiated
	their role within their wider social world. Equally indications as
	to the scale of the community have important implications for the
	nature and extent of landscape exploitation, human impact on the
	landscape and environment, and shaping of the landscape to conscious
	community agendas. Changes in the scale and nature of these features
	of the settlement allow us to approach the question of the significance
	of developments between the fifth and third millennia in terms of
	social, political and economic organisation.
	
	
	Period distributions and areas of settlement
	
	
	The basic evidence upon which we can draw to address these issues
	is provided by the overall dimensions of the tell, distribution of
	artifacts across the surface and evidence of occupation phases in
	a number of trenches across the site recorded by us but also by Mellaart
	(Leonard 19) Trench II, De Contenson, and Gustavson Gaube. Sometimes
	the precise location of those trenches is not clear, e.g. De Contenson`s
	trench, but can be arrived at approximately. Thus De Contenson`s
	trench, Trench I, was in the area of the main road junction in the
	southern part of the town probably between 50 and 100 ms SW of our
	Area D. Mellaart`s trench II-IV is shown at the far western edge
	of the mound (Leonard Fig.7) and thus is to the west of our Trench
	H. Combining this presence absence data for occupation phases with
	extant limits of the site we can draw broadly valid conclusions about
	occupation extent. 
	
	
	Given the degree of construction on the site in the 1980`s and 1990`s
	the best indications of the overall extent of the Shuna North site
	come from initial surveys in the 1950`s combined with older aerial
	photographs of the . De contenson (1960 ADAJ) gave max. length of
	the mound as1000 m NE-SW and Mellaart recorded it as 800-1000 m with
	its width approx 150 m. This would give an area for the mound of
	12-15 hectares. Given that the mound is certainly wider than these
	estimates, at least 200 m, as indicated by the aerial photographs,
	probably slightly wider than this in the SW and slightly narrower
	towards its NE tip and may even be somewhat longer, it seems likely
	that it is in the range of 16-20 hectares at conservative estimates.
	
	
	The early fifth millennium BC calibrated occupation levels have only
	been recorded in the central eastern area of the southern mound,
	in and close to the modern (1990s) bus stop. Whilst trench L to the
	c. 100 m to the NE was not excavated deeply enough to reveal the
	presence/absence of these early deposits, the trenches H and I in
	the SW and NW and Mellaart`s trench II-IV at the far SW edge of the
	mound were and no material of the fifth millennium period was found.
	De Contenson`s trench which must have been located close to but probably
	c. 100 m away from our trenches D/A suggests that the fifth millennium
	settlement focussed in this area but did not extend to the west along
	the Wadi Arab. It is thus likely to have been at least a hectare
	in area and may have been a few more hectares but was unlikely to
	exceed 5 hectares as it did not extend into the western part of the
	mound.
	
	
	Early fourth millennium material is found only in trench D and also
	may have occurred in De Contenson`s trench and it is suggested this
	phase settlement had restricted distribution.
	
	
	Early EB I material is clearly documented in our trenches A and D
	as well as Gustavson Gaube`s trench. Likewise it seems to be found
	in De Contenson`s trench. Trench H to the West but not I had material
	of this occupation phase. Whilst there may have been redeposited
	Early EB I material, no such material was apparent in discrete deposits
	preceding the late EB I material in Mellaart`s trench II-IV where
	band slip ceramics are present from earliest contexts. Likewise no
	distinct in situ phase of Early EB I ceramics was apparent in K.
	Trench H is 300 m SW of trench A and this suggests that during Early
	EB I between 3600 and 3300 BC (Chapter x) the settlement expanded
	westwards from the south central area of the mound, along the Wadi
	el Arab, thus stretching at least 400 m NE-SW to cover an area approaching
	7 hectares.
	
	
	In Mellaart`s trench II-IV (Leonard 1953 Fig 12) Late EB I ceramics
	are documented from the earliest phase (his Level 19, Layer II which
	has band slipped and Crackled ware as well as characteristic Late
	EB I holemouths) in the extreme west of the site. Late EB I in situ
	ceramics are found also in trenches slightly further north in the
	western area of the mound, our Areas H and I, and also in L in the
	NE part of the mound. Surface survey also suggests much of the 16-20
	hectare mound had Late EB I material over the surface (Mellaart ).
	Given the distinct absence of in situ Early EB I material in Mellaart`s
	Trench II and in our Area I Late EB I settlement expansion is clearly
	indicated. It seems that between 3300 and 3000 BC the settlement
	expanded to the north away from the Wadi Arab and also a little further
	to the west along the Wadi Arab to encompass c. 16-20 hectares.
	
	
	Some settlement in EB II seems likely (see Chapter x for problems
	with this period at Shuna) from sherds found in Areas H, L, and A
	but it may have been quite restricted in size. Mellaart records distinct
	EB II levels in his trench II-IV but these do not have characteristic
	EB II ceramics.
	
	
	In EB III, at least in our Khirbet Kherak dominated phase, material
	is present in Areas A (albeit redeposited, although presumably from
	fairly close by) in H and L as well as in Mellaart`s trench to the
	west, but not I and K. Thus the northern area of the mound may no
	longer have been occupied and the settlement stretched along the
	wadi al Arab over a length of more than 500 m with a probably width
	of c. 150 m. A settlement area of c. 7.5 hectares is suggested.
	
	
	Settlement layout, density and population estimates
	
	
	Because of the small scale of our soundings and modest areal extent
	of excavations in the central area, even combining plans with those
	from the adjacent Gustavson Gaube trenches it is difficult to talk
	about overall settlement layouts and characteristics. Certain points
	can still be established. In the late 6th and early 5th millennia,
	structures could be closely packed together as in phases 2-5 in Area
	D, where much of the approx. 50 m2 covered by our and Gustavson Gaube`s
	trenches was occupied by part of 3 distinct broadroom structures
	with intervening open and internal courtyard areas. In later phases
	much of these areas seems to be given over to less formally bounded
	external space as structures shifted around but were dense enough
	so that our trenches frequently contained at least part of 1 broadroom
	structure. So both areas of dense housing and more extensive open
	areas probably characterised this settlement.
	
	
	During Early EB I our area A, combined with the evidence from Gustavson
	Gaube`s trenches, witnessed a significant density of structures with
	intervening courtyard areas. In later Early EB I phases we see as
	many as 3 curvilinear/apsidal structures constructed within a few
	metres of each other, leaving only narrow passages between attesting
	to significant densities of structures in the central area of the
	site. In H to the west no domestic or other buildings are recorded
	but they may have been close by. It may well be that the western
	edges of the site were less densely occupied. Occasional substantial
	and well-apportioned multi-room habitation structures are also found
	like Building x and may have occupied more space in some areas in
	the later parts of Early EB I.
	
	
	In Late EB I a similar pattern to the later phases of early EB I is
	suggested with the central area of the site represented by some large
	multi-roomed buildings as well as more humble neighbours and in this
	Area at least very extensive unbounded areas of midden deposit. Areas
	I and H and Mellaart`s trench in the west of the site have evidence
	of structures suggesting that a significant part of the 20 hectare
	area was built up.
	
	
	We have no in situ EB II buildings further indicating the more restricted
	scale of occupation during this period.
	
	
	In situ EB III material is represented in both eastern and western
	areas by structures in Mellaart? And in G and L suggesting significant
	densities of building over a 10-15 hectare area.
	
	
	Much evidence suggests (see x.x) that the late 6th early 5th millennium
	broadrooms and their descendant EB apsidal and broadroom structures
	housed nuclear families. The circular structures of Early and Late
	EB 1 Shuna are less straight-forward of interpretation in regards
	to the nature of their occupancy and use. They may represent less
	spacious nuclear family dwellings or equally plausible were used
	several in conjunction as multi-unit family/co-residential group
	dwellings. Multi-roomed Early and Late EB I habitations may have
	provided more spacious settings for elite families or different household
	arrangements but even so domestic floor space was not generous by
	modern Middle Eastern village or town standards. 
	
	
	The above suggests internal floor area of between x and x per adult
	at Shuna from 5000-3000 BC. Population densities of c. 100 person
	per ha of settlement are seen in traditional nucleated villages of
	the recent past in the region, where structures are less or equally
	densely distributed and where individuals have as much as 10 m2 floor
	area. Comparison of the archaeological with these modern examples
	suggest people may have been at least as densely distributed per
	hectare of settlement at Shuna. 200 persons per hectare also witnessed
	in modern traditional settlements seems more realistic and 300 plausible
	as towards the maximum end of the density gradient.
	
	
	If our late 6th to early 5th millennia settlement covered 1 hectare
	(its probable minimum extent) it would have been a village of 100-300
	people using the density coefficients suggested above and at 2 hectares
	it would have had 200-600, a modest but not insubstantial village.
	
	
	In contrast Early EB I Shuna at 10 hectares presumably had a minimum
	of 1000 and up to 3000 inhabitants. Indeed given the hints of increasing
	building density in the later phases of this period an increase in
	population approaching the upper end of these figures during Early
	EB I is quite likely. Late EB I Shuna growing to at least 20 hectares
	would then have had well over 2000 inhabitants quite likely approaching
	4-6000 at its maximum period of occupation.},
	Author = {Douglas Baird and Graham Philip},
	Note = {Forthcoming},
	Owner = {arkygeek},
	Timestamp = {2009.06.11},
	Title = {Excavations at Tell esh-Shuna}}

